ULTRASONIC SENSOR:
A typical module like HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Sensor sends out high-frequency sound waves (ultrasound) and measures how long they take to return.
Humans can’t hear these sounds (above 20 kHz).

How it works (Step-by-step):
1.Send sound wave
Sensor sends ultrasonic pulse (~40 kHz)
2.Wave travels
It moves through air and hits an object
3.Echo returns
Sound reflects back to the sensor
4.Time is measured
Sensor calculates how long the echo took
5.Distance is calculated
Distance depends on time and speed of sound
Distance Formula
Distance=Speed of Sound×Time/2
Speed of sound ≈ 343 m/s
Divide by 2 → because wave goes and comes back

Ultrasonic Sensor Pin Configuration:
The commonly used module is the
HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Sensor
It has 4 pins:
Pins Overview
1.VCC (Power)
Connect to 5V
Powers the sensor
2.GND (Ground)
Connect to GND
Completes the circuit
3.TRIG (Trigger)
Input pin
Used to send ultrasonic pulse
Arduino sends a 10 microsecond HIGH signal to this pin
4.ECHO (Echo)
Output pin
Returns the signal after reflection
Arduino reads how long it stays HIGH

VCC → Power
GND → Ground
TRIG → Send signal
ECHO → Receive signal
ECHO pin gives 5V output → safe for Arduino Nano
Keep wires short for accuracy
Use stable power supply

Working Flow with Pins:
Arduino → sends pulse via TRIG
Sensor → emits sound wave
Echo returns → ECHO goes HIGH
Arduino → measures time
